titleproper.value: Guide to the Ronald Vance Papers <num>MSS.454</num>

creation.value: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace <date>2017-05-16T13:12:16</date>

abstract.value: Ronald Vance is an artist and writer active in the United States and Europe during the later half of the 20th century. This collection consists of correspondence, as well as published and unpublished writings by Vance from the late 1960s through the mid 1980s. Works of fiction present in the collection were published in literary journals including <title render="italic">Sun and Moon</title>, <title render="italic">Not Guilty Magazine</title>, and <title render="italic">Interstate Magazine</title>. The collection also includes unpublished writings, including notes and drafts related to Vance's <title render="italic">I Went to Italy and Ate Chocolate</title>.

p.value: Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

Identification of item, date; Ronald Vance Papers; MSS 454; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University.
Donated by Ronald Vance in May 2016. The accession number associated with this gift is 2016.023.

Ronald Vance is an artist and writer active during the 1960s through the 1980s. He was born in Connecticut and graduated from Yale University before lecturing on the history of art at Leicester College of Art and then moving to Italy. As of May 2016, he was living in Long Island and was retired.

This collection consists of correspondence, as well as published and unpublished writings by Ronald Vance from the late 1960s through the mid 1980s. Works of fiction present in the collection were published in literary journals including <title render="italic">Sun and Moon</title>, <title render="italic">Not Guilty Magazine</title>, and <title render="italic">Interstate Magazine</title>. The collection also includes unpublished writings, including notes and drafts related to Vance's <title render="italic">I Went to Italy and Ate Chocolate</title>.
